<div id="review_1609273938" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1609273938" />
    <a title="NAT.orious reads ☾" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/54624224-nat-orious-reads"><img alt="NAT.orious reads ☾" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606165351p2/54624224.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1609273938?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="NAT.orious reads ☾" class="user" itemprop="url" name="NAT.orious reads ☾" href="/user/show/54624224-nat-orious-reads">NAT.orious reads ☾</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781909489417" href="/book/show/23014101-the-scorch-trials">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54624224-nat-orious-reads?shelf=book-clubbing">book-clubbing</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1609273938" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13456446423325603902"><u>
  <b>2.5 STARS ★★★✬✩</b>
</u><br/><i>
  <blockquote>
<b>This book is… </b>making me doubt rereads real hard so I don&apos;t know how to and whom to recommend it to. That should say enough about my feelings regarding it.</blockquote>
</i><br/><b>⤐ <i>The reread that made me doubt rereads.</i></b><br/><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>‘Anybody else wanna pee their pants and cry for mommy?’</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br/>*raises hand shyly*<br/><br/>I did not expect this book to be such a challenge for me. Even though I listened to it while in Vienna, roaming the streets, enjoying the sun, indulging in Kaiserschmarrn, it was unbelievably toug</span>
  <span id="freeText13456446423325603902" style="display:none"><u>
  <b>2.5 STARS ★★★✬✩</b>
</u><br><i>
  <blockquote>
<b>This book is… </b>making me doubt rereads real hard so I don't know how to and whom to recommend it to. That should say enough about my feelings regarding it.</blockquote>
</i><br><b>⤐ <i>The reread that made me doubt rereads.</i></b><br><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>‘Anybody else wanna pee their pants and cry for mommy?’</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br>*raises hand shyly*<br><br>I did not expect this book to be such a challenge for me. Even though I listened to it while in Vienna, roaming the streets, enjoying the sun, indulging in Kaiserschmarrn, it was unbelievably tough for me to find the will to hit the play button. I much rather <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kNBFK2NQAKY" rel="nofollow noopener">Marcus Warner</a>-ed my way through the Natural History Museum. I basically gawked at pre-modern age animals the whole time and had a blast doing it.<br><br>Pinpointing what exactly irked me the wrong way is tough. I would like to claim the overall suspense wasn't exactly peaking but I could just as well have been distracted throughout, say 35% of <i>The Scorch Trials</i>. One might say that, consequently, it is unfair of me to judge the book by the pieces I've heard then. Pah, I disagree! Of it tales a book over a third of its pages to suck the reader in that criticism is well earned! Then again, it might have been the lack of suspense after all.<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1596617638ra/29918209.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><b>⤐ <i>What’s happening.</i></b><br><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>‘They called you the Glue’<br>‘The Glue?’<br>‘Yeah. Probably because you're kind of the glue that holds us all together.’ </i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1596617638ra/29918211.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Welcome to this sequel to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1601391529?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <i>The Maze Runner</i>
</a>, in which there is way too little on-page time for Newt, the most important character of them all.<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1596617297ra/29918150.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>It doesn't take long for our group of boys to realise that they have not successfully completed their experiment. In fact, they haven't completed it it all. The trials are still on full speed and new tests are thrown at the friends left at right. Among others, it is their trust in each other, that is truest. Thomas is doubting Theresa's motive and makes an unexpected discovery.<br>_____________________<br><b>3 STARS.</b><i> Decent read that I have neither strongly positive nor negative feelings about. Some thinks irked me and thus it does not qualify as exceptional. </i><br><br><b>2 STARS.</b><i> Definitely a disappointment. It might not even have been worth to finish for a variety of reasons. </i></span>
  <a data-text-id="13456446423325603902" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


